, whether we hired a bad lawyer, bear a slight resemblance to someone else in the world, or are not good with awkward silence. The stories of Brooks's cases and clients paint the picture of a broken justice system, one where innocence is no protection from incarceration or even the death penalty. Simultaneously relatable and disturbing, You Might Go to Prison, Even Though You're Innocent is essential reading for anyone who wants to better understand how injustice is served by our system.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 02. Mai 2023) 0aFalse imprisonmentxLaw and legislationzUnited States. 0aJudicial errorzUnited States. 0aJustice, Administration ofzUnited StatesxCriminal provisions. 7aTRUE CRIME / General.2bisacsh  aAmerican system.  aCalifornia Innocence Project.  abad lawyers.  aclass.  acriminal law.  aflawed science.  afreedom.  aincorrect.  ainjustice.  aprison reform.  aproblems with our justice system.  arace.  asentencing.  asocial inequality.  awrongful convictions.  ayou got the wrong person.1 aScheck,, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertUniversity of California Press Complete eBook-Package 2023z978311079134140uhttps://doi.org/10.1525/9780520386846?locatt=mode:legacy40uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9780520386846423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/cover/isbn/9780520386846/original  a978-3-11-079134-1  University of California Press Complete eBook-Package 2023b2023  aEBA_UCA_YUP  aGBV-deGruyter-alles  aZDB-23-UCY